  "body": "This is something I've been kicking around for a while. One annoying thing about the current MyEtherWallet site is that in order to do something as simple as add a gas limit for an ICO, change gas price ranges, add a new token, or change a node's URL, we need to push a whole new release. If it's something pretty critical, such as updating a token's contract address, old versions that have been downloaded are left high and dry.\r\n\r\nI propose that we move out the following items to an API that loads the data from https://github.com/MyEtherWallet/ethereum-lists for the following things:\r\n* Announcement banner, requested immediately\r\n* Node list, requested immediately\r\n* Gas defaults, requested immediately (Assuming we don't migrate to ethgasstation or something)\r\n* Network tokens, requested on account unlock\r\n* Contract ABIs, requested on contracts page\r\n\r\nHowever, I think we should continue to ship with the data in the bundle for offline cases, or if the API is down. We can pop up a message that lets the user know that some data may be out of date, and just revert back to the old data. That way whatever version we ship will just have whatever data is in ethereum-lists at that time.\r\n\r\nLet me know what y'all think.",
